Data Science Pipeline Tutorial: Analyzing Police Shootings from 2015 to 2020¶

CMSC320 Spring 2021

Written and Coded by Rohan Angajala and Anu Basil

Introduction¶

Welcome to our tutorial through the data science pipeline. For this tutorial, we walk through important steps in data manipulation, exploratory data analysis, investigating trends and testing hypothesis. The topic we study to perform this analysis is one that is a very relevant and heavily discussed topic in recent times. We examine data on police shootings from 2015 to 2020. Each row of the data corresponds to an individual shooting and includes information such as date of the shooting, as well as race and age demographics about the alleged perpetrator that was shot. Our intent is not to draw conclusions about police shootings based on this data such as claiming that a certain variable definitely increases the likelihood of being shot, but rather to investigate the trends across the data and make observations about the shootings that could then potentially be used in the future.

Let's get started!

Data Collection¶

First, we will need to read in our dataset using the Pandas library. We use a dataset from Kaggle.com, a popular machine learning and data science website. You can find the dataset here: https://www.kaggle.com/ahsen1330/us-police-shootings.

Download the CSV file from this website and import it into the current directory. Afterwards, we read in the csv file into a Pandas DataFrame with pd.read_csv.

Data Management/Representation¶

Let's start by checking if there are any necessary modifications to consider in our data (e.g. missing data). Missing or malicious data can be problematic because as we move into plotting and data analysis, these values can cause unintended consequences, or in the case of missing values that show up as NaN, it could cause errors. Let's first check for NaN values with the following command.

Perfect! Now as you can see in the rightmost column we have values organized by year. Now, let's add a column which categorizes individual shootings by the age group of the alleged perpetrator. That is, let's group up all our ages into groups such as 0-20 years old, 20-40 years old, etc., and assign each shooting the appropriate age group based on the age column. Pandas.cut is useful for this task. We'll assign cut values 1,2,3,4,5 to represent groups age 0-20, 20-40, 40-60, 60-80, and 80-100, respectively.

Exploratory Data Analysis¶

Now we can use powerful tools across Pandas and Matplotlib to investigate some trends based on the data we have. Let's start by examining the number of shootings by gender.

In [10]:
#create arrays to store rows of male and female victims separately
male_arr = []
female_arr = []
for index,row in data.iterrows():
    if row['gender'] == 'M':
        male_arr.append(row)
    else:
        female_arr.append(row)
In [11]:
#set up values for bar graph to use later
data_male_female = {'Male':len(male_arr), 'Female':len(female_arr)}
courses = list(data_male_female.keys())
values = list(data_male_female.values())
 
# creating the bar plot
plt.bar(courses, values, color ='deepskyblue')
 
plt.xlabel("Victim Gender")
plt.ylabel("Number of shootings")
plt.title("Victim Gender vs. Number of Shootings from 2015-2020")
plt.show()

Here we have a bar graph of the gender vs. number of shootings. This shows us that there are a disproportionate number of male victims that were shot by police. We can see that there are over 4000 males in our data set but only less than 500 females. Assuming that all other things are equal, we can see there likely is a higher chance that the shot victim is male.

Let's now look into trends relating to age and year in our data.

In [12]:
#create scatter plot
data.plot(kind='scatter', x='year', y='age', color="firebrick", title= "Year Shot vs. Age of Shot Victim")
Out[12]:
<AxesSubplot:title={'center':'Year Shot vs. Age of Shot Victim'}, xlabel='year', ylabel='age'>

We graphed a scatter plot of the year of each shooting vs. the age of the victim. We can see here that there is not much of a difference in age range of these victims over the years, which a few small exceptions. There was an older person shot in 2017 than all other years. Also, 2017 and 2015 both had an unusually young victim. This being said, there is little differences in the age of shot victims over the years as seen in this graph. It might be more beneficial if we could see the numbers of victims in a certain age group. For example, maybe there were more younger victims in earlier years and older victims in later years. This is not something that we can tell from this graph.

A better way to represent this plot would be as a violin plot. A violin plot is a type of plot that allows you to show multiple distributions within one plot, where each distribution appears in the format of a distribution curve that allows you to see the modes where the most data values lie. Each distribution is also a type of boxplot however, showing the spread of data and using markers to represent different quartiles. Let's do a violin plot of year vs. age below.

In [13]:
#group by year
year_group = data.groupby ('year') 
yearly_ages = year_group.apply(lambda x: list(x['age']))

#create violin plot
plt.violinplot(yearly_ages.values,list(map(int,list(yearly_ages.index))),widths=0.5,showmeans=True)
plt.xlabel("Year")
plt.ylabel("Victim Age")
plt.title("Violin Plot for Victim Age vs. Year")
plt.show()

The curves associated with each distribution tell us which ages show up most often in those distributions. It would appear that these modes are roughly the same across all the years, between 30 and 40 years old. We can see that 2017 had slightly more spread in age but this was due to outliers beyond age 80 (since the distribution of data is very low beyond age 50). So, based on this we can observe that the ages of police shooting victims has not changed noticeably with time.

Can we find that age is changing with respect to some other variable? Let's find out! Let's create a violin plot again, this time using the state that the shootings occurred in as the x-axis and still plotting age distributions.

It's also interesting to see that North Dakota has a very concentrated killing distribution around age 30-35.

age_group = data.groupby('age') #group by age
age_dict = {} #dictionary to keep track of armed counts per age
for row in age_group.armed.value_counts().index:
  if row[0] not in age_dict:
    age_dict[row[0]] = [0,0]
  val0 = age_dict[row[0]][0]
  val1 = age_dict[row[0]][1]
  if row[1] == 'unarmed': #increment if unarmed
    val0 += 1
  else: #armed count 
    val1 += 1
  age_dict[row[0]] = [val0, val1]

It would seem that from our analysis so far, demographics information has proven useful to look like, such as age distributions varying by race. So, let's introduce another similar variable from our data, state, which we can access from the column we created earlier in the tutorial. Let's create a bar chart to view the number of police shootings by state in the 5 year span.

In [22]:
plt.figure(figsize=(20,5))
cts = data['state'].value_counts(sort=False) #get number of shootings (rows of data) per state
plt.bar(cts.index, cts.values, color ='deepskyblue') #Plot counts
plt.xlabel("State")
plt.ylabel("Number of shootings")
plt.title("State vs. Number of Shootings")
plt.show()

This chart provides us with a great visualization of the number of shootings by state. It's easy to see that California has the most number of shootings, and then Texas and Florida follow. States like Rhode Island and state capitol Washington D.C. are among the states with the lowest number of police shootings. While we can't say for sure, it is reasonable to assume that this trend might have something to do with the populations and sizes of these states. California, Texas and Florida are among the largest states in the United States, and Rhode Island is among the smallest. Washington D.C., being a city, undoubtedly is small in size too. So, the above graphic, while interesting to look at, isn't really a great way for us to compare number of police shootings across states individually, because we can't make sense of other kinds of trends due to this large contributing factor of population size (a larger population could mean more criminals which could mean more shootings).

To be able to compare number of shootings across states meaningfully, we will introduce standardization into our data analysis. Standardizing against a variable, in our case the state, will allow us to compare number of shootings on the same scale, rather than have the large outliers such as California due to reasons such as population. In the following code excerpt, we will take the number of shootings for a given year,state combination, and subtract the average number of shootings in that state across the 5 years from it, and then take this result and divide by the standard deviation of the shootings in that state. This is the standard methodology used when computing standardized scores for a variable.

In [23]:
#Group by state and year, and gather corresponding counts of data
standard_df = data.groupby(['state','year']).size().reset_index().rename(columns={0:'count'})
avg_ct = standard_df.groupby('state')['count'].mean() #calculate averages per state
std_dev = standard_df.groupby('state')['count'].apply(np.std) #calculate standard deviations per state
standardized_counts = []
#Assembling standardized count of killings by state with following formula:
# ((number of shootings in year i in state j) - (average # of shootings in state j)) / (std. dev of shootings in state j)
for i in range(0,len(standard_df['year'])):
  x = standard_df['count'][i]
  standardized_counts.append((x-avg_ct[standard_df['state'][i]])/std_dev[standard_df['state'][i]])
standard_df['standardized_counts'] = standardized_counts

294 rows × 4 columns

Let's now plot the obtained standardized scores for number of shootings across states. In our plot, 0 would represent the mean (since standardization is essentially a way of creating a normal distribution centered at 0), so states below it would have relatively lower number of police shootings on this new scale we obtained, and states above it would have a higher number of police shootings on the scale.

We can see that it was in fact important that we standardize by states, because states like California and Texas that appeared to be very high in police shootings are in fact not that high when compared on the same scale (ignoring factors such as population). Rather, states like Minnesota and West Virginia are high in number of police shootings.

While in the graph above, we saw that there were a significant number of white people being killed, here we can see that by population, more black people are being killed.

Hypothesis Testing and Machine Learning¶

We will now perform some testing on our data to see if there may be some reasonable relationships that we can assume and then use them to predict based on unseen data. Let us start by investigating if we can perform linear regression. We use the Seaborn library to create a HeatMap using the numerical data from our dataset. A HeatMap is a way of creating a table that shows how strong the correlation between two variables is.

In [33]:

Based on this HeatMap, it would seem that all pairs of numerical variables from our data have very weak correlation with one another. The only strong correlation that shows up is between year and ID, but we disregard that because ID is simply the index of each data row and is not a meaningful variable. The other one is age and cut but this makes sense since cut was created based on age, so again this is not meaningful.

While the HeatMap shows that there isn't a lot of correlation, let's still run a hypothesis test to verify this. We decided to create a hypothesis test for the two main numeric variables that were in our data set, age and year. We will now fit a linear regression model of year vs. age range, and test for a relationship between year and age range. The null hypothesis would be that there is no linear relationship between year and age range. We chose an alpha level of 0.05 to test the significance.

In [34]:
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression

#store the values that we would like to use for our linear regression
x = data.year.values
x = x.reshape(x.size, 1)
y = data.cut.values
y = y.reshape(y.size)

#fit linear regression
reg = LinearRegression().fit(x,y)
pred = reg.predict(x)
print(reg.intercept_)
print(reg.coef_)

[0.00596448]
In [35]:
from scipy.stats import spearmanr

stat, p = spearmanr(data.cut.values, data.year.values) #conduct hypothesis test
print('stat=%.3f, p=%.3f' % (stat, p))
if p > 0.05: #compare to our p value
    print('Do not reject Ho')
else:
    print('Reject Ho')

stat=0.011, p=0.428
Do not reject Ho

Our obtained p-value is greater than our alpha significance level (the acceptable chance of a Type 1 Error), therefore, we do not reject the null hypothesis of there being no relation between years and age range. Based on our data this makes since, since in our EDA we saw in multiple plots that with respect to year, age distributions were roughly the same. There does not seem to be a difference in the ages of the shot victims based on year. We do not see any notable increases or decreases throughout the years so it makes sense that there would not be a very suitable linear regression that we could fit. When we did the hypothesis test, we confirmed that there is no relationship between the years and age range of shot victims in our data, all other things being equal.

Conclusion¶

We were able to analyze information about how the number of people that were shot by the police fluctuated with different variables such as age and mental illness, as well as view different combinations of variables such as race and time. The purpose of this tutorial was to analyze any trends and common patterns in this data set. Throughout the tutorial, we found that there are many common characteristics that many of the people that were shot by the police had. For example, based on the data, we found that there is a higher proportion of black people in the United States getting shot by the police even though just the number of white people shot by police is higher. It was extremely important that we did not stop at the bar chart showing counts of police shootings by the victim's race, and rather added a plot that showed the races' counts relative to their population. Not accounting for such factors is easily misleading in data science, and can suppress meaningful interpretations.

Similarly, standardization accounted for states' populations and revealed that states like California that had very high counts of police shootings were actually lower compared to other states after fitting states' data to the same scale, showing that states like Minnesota actually had more police shootings. Plotting these standardized counts on a choropleth geographical map also showed that levels of police shooting activity often seem to be associated with the region.

We saw from our application of hypothesis testing and machine learning that while our data did have many trends discussed in the EDA stage, it was difficult to draw relationships from a mathematical standpoint. This is why it is difficult to predict other variables from this dataset.

These are just some of the many observations and insights we were able to gather from our data analysis in this tutorial. Police shootings is a very relevant and controversial topic right now, and certainly some of the insights drawn from this data analysis could be used in the future to look further into the topic. For example, the clusters of the country which had higher standardized counts of police shootings could be examined by the federal government and those could be the primary targets for potential changes in laws or experiments in changing the approach to policing. From our Machine Learning stage we saw that it can often be difficult to predict factors with surity, however data analysis can still help narrow down variables, such as to individual states, and set the stage for further analysis.
